00:25:25.057 --> 00:25:26.640
KIMBER LOCKHART:
It's a good question,

00:25:26.640 --> 00:25:31.465
do women have more
advantages than men?

00:25:31.465 --> 00:25:35.640
You know, I think it's a wash.

00:25:35.640 --> 00:25:40.020
There are some things that have
been incredibly beneficial.

00:25:40.020 --> 00:25:42.860
People like to write about
women in computer science,

00:25:42.860 --> 00:25:43.540
I've found.

00:25:43.540 --> 00:25:47.770
So I get way more PR than
my male counterparts--

00:25:47.770 --> 00:25:50.660
kind of cool.

00:25:50.660 --> 00:25:53.820
But on the other hand,
I'll be in discussions

00:25:53.820 --> 00:25:56.480
and you'll see
some of the things

00:25:56.480 --> 00:25:59.310
that Sheryl Sandberg
shares in "Lean In"

00:25:59.310 --> 00:26:02.254
where women are perceived
as more emotional or more

00:26:02.254 --> 00:26:03.670
aggressive than
they actually are.

00:26:03.670 --> 00:26:05.630
I've seen that in the workplace.

00:26:05.630 --> 00:26:09.040
And ultimately, you are an
individual, you are unique,

00:26:09.040 --> 00:26:10.990
you have strengths,
you have weaknesses.

00:26:10.990 --> 00:26:12.770
Who you are, what
your gender is,

00:26:12.770 --> 00:26:16.330
is just another
dimension of that.

00:26:16.330 --> 00:26:20.340
And I'd say, not worry about.

00:26:20.340 --> 00:26:22.310
And if you believe
that it will be a wash

00:26:22.310 --> 00:26:23.810
and that you're
just as likely to be

00:26:23.810 --> 00:26:26.510
as successful as
any other person,

00:26:26.510 --> 00:26:28.794
I think you're more
likely to get there.

00:26:36.536 --> 00:26:37.410
AUDIENCE: Hi, Kimber.

00:26:37.410 --> 00:26:40.250
So my question is as
a junior developer

00:26:40.250 --> 00:26:43.450
who just got out of
college, if I kind of want

00:26:43.450 --> 00:26:45.220
to be a manager in
the future, what

00:26:45.220 --> 00:26:49.530
are the specific steps
or advice I can use.

00:26:49.530 --> 00:26:51.890
Let's say I mean a relatively
big company where there

00:26:51.890 --> 00:26:53.640
are managers, there
are a lot of managers.

00:26:53.640 --> 00:26:58.194
So what are the things I
can do to go to that point.

00:26:58.194 --> 00:26:59.360
KIMBER LOCKHART: Absolutely.

00:26:59.360 --> 00:27:02.920
So if you're a junior
developer, what kinds of things

00:27:02.920 --> 00:27:03.650
can you do?

00:27:03.650 --> 00:27:06.550
Well, one is to get
really good at your job.

00:27:06.550 --> 00:27:08.560
So a lot of moving
into leadership

00:27:08.560 --> 00:27:12.220
is based on being good
at what you do now.

00:27:12.220 --> 00:27:15.370
It's a prerequisite,
it's not everything.

00:27:15.370 --> 00:27:17.470
Another thing that
you might do is really

00:27:17.470 --> 00:27:19.950
observe the behavior of
the managers and leaders

00:27:19.950 --> 00:27:21.550
that you look up to.

00:27:21.550 --> 00:27:25.330
Another thing you might do is
notice where there's problems.

00:27:25.330 --> 00:27:28.980
Engineers are problem solvers
by nature but so many of us

00:27:28.980 --> 00:27:32.390
don't take the time to go
outside of the code, outside

00:27:32.390 --> 00:27:36.760
of the project, and see that
this process is really broken.

00:27:36.760 --> 00:27:39.010
I can probably fix it.

00:27:39.010 --> 00:27:40.750
And it's that level
of considering

00:27:40.750 --> 00:27:44.130
yourself empowered to solve
organizational problems that

00:27:44.130 --> 00:27:47.410
will make you into a person
that people start to notice,

00:27:47.410 --> 00:27:50.700
and will start to get you into
more and more leadership roles.

00:27:55.430 --> 00:27:56.355
Any other questions?

00:27:56.355 --> 00:27:57.260
There we go.

00:27:57.260 --> 00:27:58.950
AUDIENCE: In your
leadership journey,

00:27:58.950 --> 00:28:01.040
what is it that you
know now that you

00:28:01.040 --> 00:28:03.712
wish you had known
10 years back?

00:28:03.712 --> 00:28:05.170
KIMBER LOCKHART:
Most of the things

00:28:05.170 --> 00:28:07.200
I just shared with
you, actually.

00:28:07.200 --> 00:28:08.700
When I was making
this presentation,

00:28:08.700 --> 00:28:11.350
I said what do I wish I knew?

00:28:11.350 --> 00:28:13.270
And it was a lot
of those things.

00:28:13.270 --> 00:28:17.752
The overarching thing I wish
I knew-- I was in college.

00:28:17.752 --> 00:28:19.460
And I was trying to
determine if I wanted

00:28:19.460 --> 00:28:22.880
to be a product
manager or an engineer.

00:28:22.880 --> 00:28:24.940
Anybody ever wrestled with that?

00:28:24.940 --> 00:28:27.580
Yeah, it tends to be a pretty
typical thing, especially

00:28:27.580 --> 00:28:30.950
in the women in tech circles.

00:28:30.950 --> 00:28:36.530
And I wish I would have known
that engineering leadership,

00:28:36.530 --> 00:28:39.850
engineering management, becoming
a director of engineering,

00:28:39.850 --> 00:28:43.710
running whole engineering
teams, was a viable career path.

00:28:43.710 --> 00:28:46.380
Because it achieves
a lot of what

00:28:46.380 --> 00:28:49.220
I like in terms of
interacting with people,

00:28:49.220 --> 00:28:52.860
and marries it with still
being extremely technical.

00:28:52.860 --> 00:28:55.690
I may not write code every
day, but I'm sitting in there,

00:28:55.690 --> 00:28:58.960
I'm making decisions, I'm
asking the hard questions.

00:28:58.960 --> 00:29:02.510
So I wish that I knew that this
career path existed, because I

00:29:02.510 --> 00:29:05.090
would have saved a whole lot of
time wrestling with what else

00:29:05.090 --> 00:29:05.940
I wanted to do.

00:29:11.290 --> 00:29:12.130
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:29:12.130 --> 00:29:15.320
So for someone who is starting
out as a software engineer,

00:29:15.320 --> 00:29:17.800
you tend to actually go
on the technical part

00:29:17.800 --> 00:29:19.800
because you are shielded
off from so many things

00:29:19.800 --> 00:29:22.030
if you just stay
this way, and you

00:29:22.030 --> 00:29:23.410
get to do what
you like the most.

00:29:23.410 --> 00:29:25.560
But with someone with
that mindset, what

00:29:25.560 --> 00:29:27.560
is the one thing
that you would say

00:29:27.560 --> 00:29:31.030
is the brightest side
of just moving up

00:29:31.030 --> 00:29:33.530
on to the management part.

00:29:33.530 --> 00:29:37.274
KIMBER LOCKHART: So if
you love what you do,

00:29:37.274 --> 00:29:39.690
I'm not sure I'd be overly
concerned about doing something

00:29:39.690 --> 00:29:41.010
different.

00:29:41.010 --> 00:29:43.580
That's sort of my guide.

00:29:43.580 --> 00:29:47.200
At the same time, if you are
scared of doing something else,

00:29:47.200 --> 00:29:51.250
that's your first red flag that
maybe you should consider it.

00:29:51.250 --> 00:29:53.140
And if you live your
life according to that,

00:29:53.140 --> 00:29:55.182
you're probably going to
be in pretty good shape.

00:30:05.520 --> 00:30:08.430
AUDIENCE: So you talked a
little bit about how it's easier

00:30:08.430 --> 00:30:11.050
to move horizontally
than vertically,

00:30:11.050 --> 00:30:13.954
but as you climb up those levels
of leadership, if at some point

00:30:13.954 --> 00:30:15.370
you realize that
it's not what you

00:30:15.370 --> 00:30:17.530
want to do but you know
that now, at this point,

00:30:17.530 --> 00:30:20.520
you've got teams upon teams
resting upon your decision,

00:30:20.520 --> 00:30:22.930
does it become more
difficult in any way

00:30:22.930 --> 00:30:26.350
to shift and to change
entirely what you want to do,

00:30:26.350 --> 00:30:29.580
if you take that leap and
you climb all the way up?

00:30:29.580 --> 00:30:32.790
KIMBER LOCKHART: There's sort of
two answers that I'll give you.

00:30:32.790 --> 00:30:35.300
One is that if you
have the opportunity

00:30:35.300 --> 00:30:38.340
to move into management, and
you want to give it a try,

00:30:38.340 --> 00:30:42.900
and that's what you've set your
aim on, by all means do it.

00:30:42.900 --> 00:30:45.620
If your company knows
what they're doing,

00:30:45.620 --> 00:30:47.600
they will have a track back out.

00:30:47.600 --> 00:30:51.350
It's very typical that engineers
will think that this is

00:30:51.350 --> 00:30:54.070
something they want to do and
then get into it and either

00:30:54.070 --> 00:30:56.440
decide they love
it or really don't.

00:30:56.440 --> 00:30:58.450
I have two people
on my team actually

00:30:58.450 --> 00:31:00.690
who have become managers
that I have transitioned

00:31:00.690 --> 00:31:02.720
back out to individual
contributors.

00:31:02.720 --> 00:31:04.550
Not because they
were doing a bad job,

00:31:04.550 --> 00:31:07.070
but because it was clear
in our conversations

00:31:07.070 --> 00:31:08.840
that there just was not a fit.

00:31:08.840 --> 00:31:11.180
They didn't like it, and
they weren't as effective

00:31:11.180 --> 00:31:13.950
as they could have been
if they did like it.

00:31:13.950 --> 00:31:17.280
Now to your question of
moving further up and what

00:31:17.280 --> 00:31:18.710
you do when you move further up.

00:31:18.710 --> 00:31:21.235
I think what's really
nice about our industry is

00:31:21.235 --> 00:31:23.290
that opportunities are
so plentiful that you

00:31:23.290 --> 00:31:26.690
can kind of do
whatever you want.

00:31:26.690 --> 00:31:29.120
But it does become
harder to make

00:31:29.120 --> 00:31:31.840
a move when you
have a large team.

00:31:31.840 --> 00:31:35.250
So as you start to have
bigger and bigger teams,

00:31:35.250 --> 00:31:39.840
you have to have more
specific plans for what

00:31:39.840 --> 00:31:43.030
happens if you need to extract
yourself from that situation.

00:31:43.030 --> 00:31:45.340
So that might mean, you've
been there for 10 years,

00:31:45.340 --> 00:31:46.798
you want to do
something else, it's

00:31:46.798 --> 00:31:49.260
time for you to move on
to your next opportunity.

00:31:49.260 --> 00:31:51.980
You are measured by how
you leave your team.

00:31:51.980 --> 00:31:54.420
And so leaving your
team in great shape

00:31:54.420 --> 00:31:57.830
is something that follows
you as you move on.

00:32:06.020 --> 00:32:08.570
AUDIENCE: You've
talked a lot about sort

00:32:08.570 --> 00:32:10.780
of moving through
your career and how

00:32:10.780 --> 00:32:12.060
things change over time.

00:32:12.060 --> 00:32:15.100
And 10 years into my
career I'm realizing

00:32:15.100 --> 00:32:18.160
that I evaluated whether I
was doing the right things

00:32:18.160 --> 00:32:19.660
or whether I wanted
to change things

00:32:19.660 --> 00:32:23.710
a lot more earlier in
my career than I do now.

00:32:23.710 --> 00:32:27.014
And so the question
I have is, how often

00:32:27.014 --> 00:32:28.680
do you think it's
healthy to really look

00:32:28.680 --> 00:32:30.959
at what you're doing
and sort of reality

00:32:30.959 --> 00:32:32.750
check yourself in the
direction that you're

00:32:32.750 --> 00:32:34.500
going as you progress
through your career,

00:32:34.500 --> 00:32:36.962
and how do you change
that over time?

00:32:36.962 --> 00:32:38.670
KIMBER LOCKHART: So
most of these answers

00:32:38.670 --> 00:32:40.040
have been solely my opinion.

00:32:40.040 --> 00:32:43.340
This one is perhaps
even more so.

00:32:43.340 --> 00:32:45.240
This is just what I do.

00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:50.900
I find that if I go
longer than six months,

00:32:50.900 --> 00:32:52.680
I haven't thought
about it enough.

00:32:52.680 --> 00:32:56.750
If I go less long than six
months, I drive myself crazy.

00:32:56.750 --> 00:32:59.850
So I ended up at six months.

00:32:59.850 --> 00:33:02.800
You could try your birthday
every year, try New Year's.

00:33:02.800 --> 00:33:04.300
New Year's is great,
because you get

00:33:04.300 --> 00:33:06.530
to set goals and think about
your life all at the same time.

00:33:06.530 --> 00:33:07.238
Favorite holiday.

00:33:09.780 --> 00:33:13.262
But I do recommend
having some frequency

00:33:13.262 --> 00:33:15.470
that you evaluate what it
is you're doing, especially

00:33:15.470 --> 00:33:16.940
because you can
get in a situation

00:33:16.940 --> 00:33:19.590
where you're not making a
move because you're scared

00:33:19.590 --> 00:33:22.070
of the next move, as opposed
to because you're really

00:33:22.070 --> 00:33:23.690
happy with what you're doing.

00:33:23.690 --> 00:33:26.700
And really, that's the
time to be concerned.

00:33:26.700 --> 00:33:29.020
If you're happy doing what
you're doing, have at it.

00:33:32.230 --> 00:33:32.890
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:33:32.890 --> 00:33:35.890
Have you ever in your
career have seen women

00:33:35.890 --> 00:33:39.770
not moving up in the
hierarchy because people

00:33:39.770 --> 00:33:42.650
in the management thinks
that they are-- because she

00:33:42.650 --> 00:33:45.250
is a woman and she needs
time with her family,

00:33:45.250 --> 00:33:48.100
and she may not be able to give
hundred percent to this job

00:33:48.100 --> 00:33:49.100
profile?

00:33:49.100 --> 00:33:52.100
Have you ever come
across this situation?

00:33:52.100 --> 00:33:53.380
KIMBER LOCKHART: No.

00:33:53.380 --> 00:33:54.360
Not explicitly.

00:33:54.360 --> 00:33:58.640
Have I ever come across
women paying a penalty

00:33:58.640 --> 00:34:01.940
in moving up in the ladder
because they might want

00:34:01.940 --> 00:34:05.610
to spend more time with their
children and their family?

00:34:05.610 --> 00:34:07.180
Usually I see it
more the other way

00:34:07.180 --> 00:34:11.250
around, where women don't
approach the opportunity

00:34:11.250 --> 00:34:12.750
or don't plan for
the opportunity

00:34:12.750 --> 00:34:15.460
because they're
worried about it.

00:34:15.460 --> 00:34:16.699
And I'm lucky.

00:34:16.699 --> 00:34:20.440
I work at an extremely
thoughtful company,

00:34:20.440 --> 00:34:22.780
an extremely supportive
company of women.

00:34:22.780 --> 00:34:27.730
And I got to form that
from a very early stage.

00:34:27.730 --> 00:34:31.340
But if you look at-- my
leadership team is half women.

00:34:31.340 --> 00:34:34.389
In fact, the team that I'm
a part of, the team that

00:34:34.389 --> 00:34:37.449
sort of reports to the head
of engineering is half women.

00:34:37.449 --> 00:34:39.989
I honestly don't know
how that came to be,

00:34:39.989 --> 00:34:43.909
but it's an extremely exciting
dynamic to be a part of.

00:34:43.909 --> 00:34:47.340
And actually what I
find is, of the women

00:34:47.340 --> 00:34:52.500
that stay in technical
roles, many of them

00:34:52.500 --> 00:34:56.370
have other sides to
their personality

00:34:56.370 --> 00:34:59.380
that make them good leaders.

00:34:59.380 --> 00:35:02.810
So this is by all means not
a sweeping, generalization

00:35:02.810 --> 00:35:03.660
statement.

00:35:03.660 --> 00:35:06.680
There are people of all
profiles of all genders,

00:35:06.680 --> 00:35:09.060
but I keep accidentally
having women

00:35:09.060 --> 00:35:10.620
move into leadership
roles on my team

00:35:10.620 --> 00:35:12.203
because they keep
being the people who

00:35:12.203 --> 00:35:13.910
are good at organizing
other people.

00:35:16.950 --> 00:35:19.760
So actually, I had to
go in, and at one point

00:35:19.760 --> 00:35:21.815
I had all women
as Scrum Masters,

00:35:21.815 --> 00:35:23.190
and somebody came
to me and said,

00:35:23.190 --> 00:35:24.690
do you realize you have this?

00:35:24.690 --> 00:35:28.520
And I said, no, I didn't
realize I had that.

00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:31.320
Maybe I should
encourage some guys.

